What happened was that I was flagged by adding the link to the original source of music that was used in my video. In editing mode, I copied and pasted the link in the discription box. Beside it, it says that, quote on quote, "but links are ok". I did this because I do not want to be plagiarizing the music used in my video. But the automated system flagged it as a spam. I don't use Vimeo and would rather prefer YouTube instead, but we needed to use Vimeo in order to embedded on to Behance. And on Behance is where we post our assignments for our Intro to Digital Media and Digial Films courses (that I am currently taking). But with my Vimeo account locked and unable to post any videos, I am surely to fall behind my fellow peers. I can make other accounts, but I am concerned that those account may get flagged as a "spam" as well. Anyways, onto the actual review 3 star rating: This type of media platform is very similar to YouTube. So I'm giving this an okay rating because I do not have any past problems with this app/website. Easy to use. Easy to summit videos onto your Behance page. Why it is a 3 star rating: Unlike YouTube, this has an automatic report system, meaning, actual people do not report your video, but the bots do. This can work in some cases, but most do not. And another thing that I would like to mention is that they do NOT give you any WARNINGS. That is the biggest difference between YouTube and Vimeo. YouTube gives you 3 strikes for your behaviour and 3 more for the content of your channel. On Vimeo on the other hand, does not have this type of system. No warnings, no strikes, nothing. And you would have to wait for an ACTUAL person that works at Vimeo to mannually unflag your account. As of today, my account is currently under "review" and I have to wait 3 business days to get a message.

The real problem is with Vimeo's phone app. Vimeo as a service is a great platform for hosting content. As a creator it allows direct payment for content which is great. However, Vimeo's phone application does a great disservice to this goal.   Poor buffering over chromecast, no ability to close you...Full ReviewThe real problem is with Vimeo's phone app. Vimeo as a service is a great platform for hosting content. As a creator it allows direct payment for content which is great. However, Vimeo's phone application does a great disservice to this goal.   Poor buffering over chromecast, no ability to close your phone while playing a video. This and other issues discussed throughout this review section leave the consumer asking why do I use this platform? The app itself sadly lags behind competitors. Currently there is a shift towards increased consumption of content over mobile devises, faults with an app like those experienced here will eventually hurt the platforms bottom line.
